haped international humanitarianism. In revealing that modern humanitarianism and its conception of childhood are products of the early twentieth-century imperial economy, Saving the Children argues that the contemporary aid sector must reckon with its past if it is to forge a new future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHumanitarianismxPolitical aspectsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107391520 cprintz978052034371940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520975118?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520975118423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520975118/original  a978-3-11-073915-2  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075408-7  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2021  aZDB-23-DGGb2021